{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":36161,"record_hash":"sha256:6092ab4015496107c87952bf41bcf1cbb433f9be10c332471681a54458fef5bf","timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:21:01.210Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"I think your instinct is right: **capture time is the wrong moment to create a branch relationship**, except when the user explicitly provides a target. At capture time we know “this session happened near this repo.” We do not yet know which generated ideas or edits the user will keep, split, move, amend, or discard.\n\nThe better model is:\n\n```text\nproject\n  session A\n  session B\n\nchange / commit / PR / branch target\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = { session A, session B }\n```\n\nBut mentally, that edge should mean **“this session contributed context to this code/review object”**, not “this session owns this branch.”\n\n**Best Anchor**\nA branch is probably not the best primary anchor. Branches move, get renamed, get rebased, and in GitButler multiple branches can be active in one worktree. A better order is:\n\n1. **GitButler change id** if available  \n   Best for amend/rebase because it is meant to survive commit rewriting.\n\n2. **Commit id** as fallback  \n   Good for plain Git, but less stable across amend/rebase.\n\n3. **PR id / review target** once known  \n   Good for review UI, often derived from the changes/commits in the PR.\n\n4. **Branch target** as a convenience index  \n   Useful for navigation, but not the deepest truth.\n\nSo for review use case, I’d expect the PR page to find sessions by taking the union of sessions attached to its changes/commits, plus any explicit PR-level attachments.\n\n**When To Associate**\nAssociation should happen at **[REDACTED:entropy] time**, not capture time.\n\nAt commit/amend time we know:\n\n- which hunks/files are actually being committed\n- which change/branch/commit target receives them\n- whether this is a new change or an amendment\n- whether there are one or many plausible recent sessions\n\nThat is much better evidence than “current branch when the transcript was captured.”\n\n**How To Decide**\nI’d use a high-precision approach:\n\n```text\ncapture session\n  -> store durable project session only\n\ncommit/amend\n  -> find recent candidate sessions\n  -> score them\n  -> attach automatically only when confidence is high\n  -> otherwise ask / suggest / attach none\n```\n\nCandidate signals could be:\n\n- session recency relative to commit/amend\n- session transcript mentions files being committed\n- tool calls touched files being committed\n- exactly one recent active agent session exists\n- user explicitly selected a session\n- agent itself invoked the GitButler commit command\n\nBut I would bias toward **false negatives over false positives**. Missing an association is annoying; a wrong association is misleading provenance.\n\n**Ambiguity**\nIf multiple sessions are plausible, attach all only when that is genuinely defensible. Otherwise show something like:\n\n```text\nPossible agent sessions:\n  [x] Claude session from 12:04, touched crates/but-agentlog\n  [ ] Codex session from 11:20, planning-only\n```\n\nFor noninteractive CLI, I’d probably default to no inferred attachment unless there is exactly one strong candidate, or the user passes something explicit.\n\n**Storage Shape**\nThe current simple set is still good as the core index:\n\n```text\n<change/commit/branch/pr target>\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\nLater, if the review UI needs trust/explainability, add optional edge metadata:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-session-link:<session-key> = {\n  \"method\": \"explicit\" | \"auto\",\n  \"operation\": \"commit\" | \"amend\" | \"pr-publish\",\n  \"created_at\": \"...\",\n  \"evidence\": \"recent-session-and-file-overlap\"\n}\n```\n\nBut I would not add that until the UI actually needs it. The set is the thing that earns its keep now.\n\n**Main Recommendation**\nDo not infer branch association during capture. Keep capture project-scoped. Add associations when GitButler performs a meaningful code operation, especially commit/amend, and prefer attaching to durable change ids over branches. Branch/PR views can then be built as unions over those lower-level relationships.\n\nThat keeps us aligned with both future use cases: handoff still starts from project sessions, while code review gets a reliable path from PR/change/commit back to the relevant session transcripts.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:21:01.210Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}